For potential application in Li metal batteries, the interfacial compatibility between the IFR-SPE and the Li metal is crucial, which could be evaluated by measuring the electrochemical impedance spectroscopy (EIS) of the Li/IFR-SPE/Li cell. Fig. 6b shows EIS results of Li/IFR-SPE/Li symmetrical cell at different aging times. The AC impedance at high frequency intercept is assigned to the bulk resistance (Rb
                     ) of IFR-SPE, whereas that in lower frequency region is related to the interfacial resistance (Ri
                     ) between Li electrode and IFR-SPE. The Ri
                      slightly increases with time within the initial five days and then becomes nearly stable with increasing aging time. This result indicates the superb compatibility of IFR-SPE to Li metal electrode. In addition, the anodic stability of the IFR-SPE is determined by linear scanning voltammetry (LSV) with a Li/IFR-SPE/SS cell at room temperature. As shown in Fig. 6c, the IFR-SPE possesses a stable oxidation decomposition onset potential of 4.12 V vs. Li/Li+, which is superior to PEO electrolyte with 3.95 V in Fig. S9.
